# {{.Name}}

A {{.Example}} Go compute-module starter generated by `foundry-cmgo`.

## Happy path

```bash
go test ./...
foundry-cmgo preview
foundry-cmgo build
foundry-cmgo inspect last
```

`foundry-cmgo preview` starts an in-process mock Foundry server, samples `data/input.csv` (1000 rows by default), runs the same `foundry` command used by the platform, and prints a compact output table. `foundry-cmgo build` intentionally builds and runs the generated Docker container by default so container-only Foundry issues are caught early; use `foundry-cmgo build --container=false` or `foundry-cmgo build --local-process` for the faster host-process path. Build uses the full configured input and commits output into local mock Foundry state.

Configuration lives in `foundry-cmgo.yaml`:

- `module.command` is the command preview/build execute.
- `inputs[].alias` and `outputs[].alias` mirror Foundry resource aliases.
- `preview.rows` controls sampled preview size.

## Local transform loop

For processor-only development you can still bypass Foundry emulation:

```bash
go run ./cmd/compute-module local --input data/input.csv --output out/output.csv
```

The same `processor.Processor` implementation is used by local and Foundry modes.

## Foundry mode

This starter expects Foundry-style environment variables when run directly:

- `FOUNDRY_URL` for local mock shorthand, or `FOUNDRY_SERVICE_DISCOVERY_V2` for platform service discovery
- `BUILD2_TOKEN`
- `RESOURCE_ALIAS_MAP`

Run the compute module directly if a mock Foundry server is already listening:

```bash
FOUNDRY_URL=http://localhost:8080 \
BUILD2_TOKEN=test/fixtures/token.txt \
RESOURCE_ALIAS_MAP=test/fixtures/alias-map.json \
go run ./cmd/compute-module foundry --output-mode {{.OutputMode}}
```

The output contract is intentionally small: `email,value,status` for dataset mode and equivalent JSON fields for stream mode.

## Advanced/debug mock Foundry plumbing

The normal path is `preview` then `build`; you usually do not need manual seed commands. They remain useful when debugging a running mock Foundry server or Docker Compose parity.

Copy a CSV into the mock Foundry dataset input layout:

```bash
foundry-cmgo seed dataset --csv data/input.csv --alias-map test/fixtures/alias-map.json --alias input
```
{{if .IsStream}}
Publish rows directly to the output stream when a mock Foundry server is running with that output RID registered as a stream:

```bash
foundry-cmgo seed stream --csv out/output.csv --alias-map test/fixtures/alias-map.json --alias output --url http://localhost:8080
```
{{end}}
Docker Compose parity still exists for multi-service container checks, but `foundry-cmgo build` already crosses the generated Dockerfile/container boundary by default:

```bash
foundry-cmgo seed dataset --csv data/input.csv --alias-map test/fixtures/alias-map.json --alias input
docker compose -f docker-compose.local.yml up --build --abort-on-container-exit
```

## Container notes

The generated Dockerfile is intentionally Debian slim, not Alpine, and targets `linux/amd64`. Foundry requires compute-module images to run as a numeric non-root user; this template defaults to `USER 5000:5000` because many Foundry-mounted token/secret files are readable by UID 5000. The official requirement is numeric non-root, not that exact UID.
